sec.p:
In 1890 Robert Koch laid out a definitive set of criteria for the identification of a pathogenic microorganism. Although subtly reworded and extended with a fourth postulate over the century that has passed,1 the postulates can be summarised as follows:


1. the bacterium must be present in all diseased individuals (but should not be isolated in healthy individuals);

2. the bacterium must be isolated from a diseased individual and grown in pure culture;

3. the bacterium must cause the specific disease when inoculated into a healthy individual;

4. the same bacterium must be re-isolated from the experimentally diseased individual.
